[2026-07-10] FIX: sent chat messages could vanish from the screen (realtime-only bug)
  Bug (user-reported, with screenshot): sent a text message in Chat and it
  never appeared in the message list - screen stayed on the "Say hi" empty
  state even after sending.
  Root cause: _send() (and the 3 media senders: _sendPhoto/_attachVideo/
  _toggleVoice) called the repository's send method, threw away the returned
  ChatMessage row, and relied ENTIRELY on the Supabase Realtime
  postgres_changes subscription to append the message to the local list. If
  the realtime channel hadn't finished (re)connecting yet, or dropped a beat
  on a flaky mobile connection, the message was genuinely saved to the DB but
  never rendered - the sender's own message could silently disappear.
  Fix - lib/features/chat/chat_screen.dart:
    - Added _appendSent(ChatMessage) - appends to _messages + scrolls to
      bottom, but only if the id isn't already present (guards against
      double-add if realtime ALSO delivers the same insert).
    - _send(), _sendPhoto(), _attachVideo(), _toggleVoice() now all capture
      the ChatMessage returned by sendTextMessage()/sendMediaMessage() and
      call _appendSent() on it immediately, instead of discarding the return
      value and waiting on realtime alone. Realtime is now purely an
      ADDITIONAL path for receiving the OTHER participant's messages (and a
      backup for your own) rather than the only path.
  Result: flutter analyze clean (same 2 pre-existing lints), flutter test
    green (2). NOT run on-device.

[2026-07-10] FIX: signing out and into a different account showed the old account's data
  Bug (user-reported): sign out, sign in as a different user -> the app kept
  showing (some of) the previous account's profile/feed/matches/etc. instead
  of the new user's.
  Root cause: NONE of the ~19 user-scoped FutureProviders in
  shared/data/repositories.dart (currentUserProvider, discoverFeedProvider,
  likedYouProvider, matchesProvider, conversationsProvider, messagesProvider,
  notificationsProvider, myPhotosProvider, myStatsProvider, etc.) depend on
  authControllerProvider's state - they only call Supabase.instance.client
  directly via their repository. Riverpod caches a FutureProvider's result
  until something explicitly invalidates it or a watched dependency changes;
  since none of these watch auth state, Riverpod had no reason to ever
  recompute them across a sign-out/sign-in. AuthController.signOut() reset
  its OWN state but never touched any of these, so any provider that had
  already resolved kept serving the previous user's cached data after a new
  user signed in.
  Fix - lib/features/auth/auth_controller.dart:
    - Added _invalidateUserScopedProviders(), which explicitly
      ref.invalidate()s every user-scoped provider: currentUserProvider,
      discoverFeedProvider, cardPhotosProvider (import from
      features/discover/discover_providers.dart), likedYouProvider,
      matchesProvider, myMatchRowsProvider, conversationsProvider,
      conversationForPartnerProvider, messagesProvider, profileByIdProvider,
      notificationsProvider, notificationPreferencesProvider,
      safetyReportsProvider, devicesProvider, profilesByCountryProvider,
      myPhotosProvider, myStatsProvider, reactionsProvider,
      callHistoryProvider, isPremiumProvider.
    - Called from signOut() (the main fix - guarantees a clean slate the
      moment a session ends) AND from signIn()/signUp() (belt-and-suspenders,
      in case any provider resolved again during the brief signed-out window
      between accounts, e.g. from a screen still mounted during the auth
      transition).
  Chose explicit invalidation over making each provider ref.watch(auth
  state) - would require touching ~19 provider definitions across multiple
  files and is easy to miss for whoever adds the 20th provider later; a
  single method in the one place that legitimately knows "identity just
  changed" is more maintainable, at the cost of needing to remember to add
  new user-scoped providers to this list too (flagged in the method's doc
  comment).
  Result: flutter analyze clean (same 2 pre-existing lints, unrelated).
    flutter test green (2, unchanged). NOT run on-device - needs two real
    accounts to verify the switch is actually clean end-to-end.

[2026-07-10] RESPONSIVENESS: fixed the 4 real overflow risks found by audit
  Context: user asked for a responsiveness pass with an explicit constraint -
  the app must look EXACTLY the same as today; no tablet/desktop redesign, no
  new breakpoints. Clarified via AskUserQuestion that "responsive" here means
  "don't overflow/clip/squish on any phone size" while keeping the existing
  448px-capped, centered phone layout untouched (already correct, confirmed
  by audit - AppShell/AuthScreen apply maxContainerWidth consistently and
  nothing bypasses it with a larger fixed width).
  Ran an Explore-agent audit across the whole lib/ tree first (not a fix
  pass) to find genuine risk points rather than guessing. Verdict: the
  codebase is mostly already responsive (chat bubbles use screenWidth*0.68,
  most grids use AspectRatio, most text Rows already use Expanded/Flexible/
  ellipsis). Only 4 real overflow risks found on narrow phones (~320px, e.g.
  iPhone SE) - everything else was low/cosmetic (wraps to 2 lines instead of
  overflowing).
  Fixes - all pure overflow guards, zero visual change at normal widths
  (nothing that already fit was touched):
    - features/discover/discover_screen.dart: card's name+age Text (large
      headlineMedium, next to an online-status dot) had no Flexible/
      ellipsis - wrapped in Flexible + maxLines:1 + TextOverflow.ellipsis.
      Highest real-overflow risk of the four (headline-size font in a fixed-
      width card).
    - shared/widgets/profile_preview_modal.dart: same pattern for the name+
      age Text next to the verified badge in the Likes/Explore preview
      sheet - wrapped in Flexible + ellipsis. Confirmed the outer
      mainAxisSize.min Column still gives the Row a finite width from the
      modal sheet, so Flexible has something real to shrink into.
    - shared/widgets/sub_page_header.dart: the shared SubPageHeader title
      was already in Expanded but had no maxLines/overflow - added
      maxLines:1 + ellipsis so a caller with wide `actions` (see next) can't
      push it into an unbounded-width crash.
    - features/subscription/subscription_screen.dart: the header's
      `actions` Row ("crown icon + Unlock Premium" label) had no
      mainAxisSize.min/Flexible - on a narrow screen this fixed-width label
      would squeeze "Choose Your Plan" down to almost nothing before the new
      ellipsis even kicks in. Added mainAxisSize.min to the Row + wrapped
      the label Text in Flexible + ellipsis so both sides degrade gracefully
      together instead of one winning by being rigid.
    - features/chat/chat_screen.dart _MediaThumb: image/video thumbnails
      were a hardcoded 200x200, which can slightly exceed the chat bubble's
      own inner width (screenWidth*0.68 minus the bubble's 14px*2 padding)
      on the narrowest phones. Now computed as
      (screenWidth*0.68 - 28).clamp(120, 200) - renders at the same 200px as
      before on any normal/large phone (the clamp's upper bound), only
      shrinks below that on genuinely narrow screens.
  Result: flutter analyze clean (same 2 pre-existing lints in
    chat_repository, unrelated). flutter test green (2, unchanged).
    flutter build apk --debug -> SUCCESS. NOT run on-device / no simulator
    width sweep performed - recommend testing at ~320px width (e.g. iPhone
    SE size in a resizable emulator, or Flutter web + browser resize) to
    visually confirm the 4 fixed spots no longer clip and everything else
    still looks pixel-identical to before.

[2026-07-10] FIX: 3 layout bugs reported with screenshots (Profile, Messages, Discover)
  Bug 1 - Profile card content not centered:
    features/profile/profile_screen.dart _profileCard(): the avatar/name/
    chips Column had no width to center against - Column sizes to its
    widest child by default, so CrossAxisAlignment.center was centering
    the content against ITSELF (effectively a no-op) rather than against
    the actual white card width, since the pencil FAB's Positioned sibling
    doesn't contribute to the Stack's sizing either. Fixed by adding
    `const SizedBox(width: double.infinity)` as the Column's first child -
    forces the Column to claim the Stack's full available width, so
    CrossAxisAlignment.center now genuinely centers against the card.
  Bug 2 - Messages chat row "BOTTOM OVERFLOWED BY 8.0 PX" (screenshotted):
    features/messages/messages_screen.dart _ChatRow: ListTile.trailing held
    a Column (time label + chevron IconButton) taller than the space
    ListTile allocates for trailing. Root cause: even with padding:zero and
    an empty BoxConstraints, IconButton still carries built-in minimum
    tap-target overhead - not actually removable via IconButton's own
    params in this Flutter version. Fixed by replacing the IconButton with
    a bare Icon + GestureDetector (no min-size inflation at all) and adding
    `minVerticalPadding: 12` to the ListTile for breathing room. Also added
    `mainAxisSize: MainAxisSize.min` to the trailing Column defensively.
  Bug 3 - Discover "Worldwide" chip/location pin misaligned under the header:
    features/discover/discover_screen.dart build(): the EMPTY-STATE branch
    (`remaining.isEmpty`, which is what the screenshot was actually showing
    - "No matches near you") built its ListView with NO padding at all,
    while the normal data branch used `EdgeInsets.fromLTRB(16,16,16,24)`.
    So _aboveCard()'s chip/pin sat flush against the screen edges only in
    the empty state, looking misaligned vs. every other screen's consistent
    16px margin. Fixed by giving the empty-state ListView the identical
    padding as the data branch.
  Result: flutter analyze clean (same 2 pre-existing lints, unrelated).
    flutter test green (2, unchanged). flutter build apk --debug -> SUCCESS.
    NOT run on-device - user should re-check all 3 screenshotted screens.

