[2026-07-10] FIX: debug APK black-screens on launch (2 root causes, both fixed)
  User reported the debug APK opens to a solid black screen instead of the
  app. Investigated and found TWO separate problems - fixed both.
  Root cause 1 (the actual black screen): every `flutter build apk --debug`
    run this session (and, it turns out, historically) was built WITHOUT
    --dart-define=SUPABASE_URL / --dart-define=SUPABASE_ANON_KEY.
    core/config/supabase_config.dart reads these via
    String.fromEnvironment(...), which is '' when not passed at build time.
    bootstrap.dart's assert() catches this in debug builds - but an assert
    thrown before runApp() in an installed APK crashes before the Flutter
    widget tree (and its red error overlay) ever renders, which is
    indistinguishable from a black screen to the user. .vscode/launch.json
    already had the correct --dart-define values for `flutter run` from the
    IDE - `flutter build apk` was just never given them. FIX: rebuilt with
    both --dart-define flags matching launch.json's known-good values.
  Root cause 2 (build kept failing before I could even test the fix): the
    Gradle "Cannot access output property ... Could not read directory path
    ...\build\app\kotlin\compileDebugKotlin\cacheable\caches-jvm\jvm\kotlin"
    error from the previous session's log entry was STILL happening, even
    after a `flutter clean` + rebuild. Root-caused this session by actually
    checking running processes (Get-Process) instead of re-trying blindly:
    found 4 stray java.exe Gradle daemon processes (under
    C:\Users\acer\.jdk\jdk-21.0.8(1)\, cmdline referencing
    .gradle\caches\...) left over from earlier interrupted build attempts,
    holding an open file lock on that exact build-cache directory - that's
    what Gradle's error was actually complaining about. `gradlew --stop`
    hadn't caught them (probably a version/project mismatch in daemon
    registry). Killed the 4 stray PIDs directly (Stop-Process -Force,
    confirmed via AskUserQuestion first since it's a process-termination
    action), then the previously-undeletable build\ directory (which
    wouldn't rm -rf even after killing them, presumably a teardown race) was
    renamed out of the way (Rename-Item, not deleted, kept as
    build_stale_<timestamp> - preferred the reversible move over a delete
    per the safety principle) so Gradle could create a fresh one. Also added
    `kotlin.incremental=false` to android/gradle.properties (approved via
    AskUserQuestion) as a standing safety net against this class of Windows
    Kotlin-incremental-cache corruption recurring - slightly slower Kotlin
    compiles, worth it given this cost 2 sessions of build failures.
  Result: `flutter build apk --debug` with both --dart-define flags -> BUILD
    SUCCEEDED (154.9s). build\app\outputs\flutter-apk\app-debug.apk exists,
    ~192MB, freshly timestamped. The renamed build_stale_<timestamp>
    directory could not be deleted afterward (still locked by something,
    not investigated further since it's inert and doesn't affect the app or
    future builds) - safe to ignore or manually delete later.
  IMPORTANT PROCESS NOTE for future sessions: `flutter build apk` (release
    OR debug) for THIS project must always include both --dart-define flags
    (SUPABASE_URL + SUPABASE_ANON_KEY, values in .vscode/launch.json) or the
    resulting APK will crash to a black screen on launch. Plain
    `flutter build apk --debug` with no flags (what every prior session in
    this log used) produces a build that ANALYZES/passes gradle but is
    non-functional when actually installed - the analyze/test/build green
    checkmarks in every earlier developer.log entry were real for code
    correctness but did NOT catch this, since Dart analysis has no way to
    know a runtime String.fromEnvironment() value will be empty.

